This policy revises and supersedes the 'HHS OCIO Policy for Information Technology (IT) Enterprise Performance Life Cycle (EPLC)' dated October 6, 2008.

This policy mandates the use of the Department of Health & Human Services (HHS) Enterprise Performance Life Cycle (EPLC) framework for information technology (IT) project management at HHS. This policy incorporates the EPLC as a partner to HHS Capital Planning and Investment Control (CPIC) and HHS Enterprise Architecture.

In October 2008, HHS issued the HHS OCIO Policy for Information Technology Enterprise Performance Life Cycle along with the EPLC Framework Overview Document that describes a structured approach to planning, managing, and overseeing HHS IT projects over their entire life cycle. The EPLC Policy, together with the EPLC Framework, serves as the authority for EPLC requirements, objectives, responsibilities, and standards for managing all IT projects at HHS. The EPLC Policy was revised in 2016 to incorporate project management elements of FITARA. Implementing the EPLC framework helps ensure the quality of HHS IT products through improved project management processes and accountability.

This policy applies to all HHS IT projects throughout the life cycle of the project, regardless of development methodology, funding source, or whether the delivered product is owned and operated by HHS or a third party acting on behalf of HHS. It applies to all HHS OPDIVs and STAFFDIVs, including contractors, interns, and organizations acting on behalf of HHS. The policy shall be implemented in accordance with HHS Acquisition Regulation (HHSAR) and other applicable laws and agreements.

All HHS IT projects shall be managed using the HHS EPLC Framework, including life cycle phases, reviews, deliverables, activities, responsibilities, and tailoring, regardless of the specific development methodology used. Projects must ensure incremental delivery of new or modified functionality at least every six months, using proven methods such as agile. This policy shall be applied in conjunction with the HHS Policy for Enterprise Architecture (EA), Capital Planning and Investment Control (CPIC), and Portfolio Management (PfM). OPDIVs and STAFFDIVs may create a more restrictive policy but not one that is less compliant than this Department Policy.

Flexibility: The EPLC is designed to provide flexibility while managing risk and accommodating project-specific needs. Structure: Projects will be managed in a structured manner using sound project management practices. Methodology: Incremental and iterative development must be prioritized under FITARA. Collaboration: Stakeholder and partner input must be integrated through all stages. Accountability/Transparency: The EPLC framework establishes accountability through defined life cycle processes.
This section defines the responsibilities of key stakeholders involved in implementing and managing the EPLC framework.

Responsible for ensuring compliance with the EPLC policy, involving stakeholders, utilizing incremental methodologies, maintaining project status, conducting phase activities and reviews, and reporting variances to governance bodies. Must develop corrective action or baseline change plans when necessary.

Responsible for ensuring alignment with mission priorities, providing funding, approving changes to cost and schedule, participating in reviews and acceptance testing, validating business requirements, and approving baseline tailoring strategies.

Responsible for ensuring EPLC transparency, implementing improvements, providing guidance, ensuring effective incremental development practices, and maintaining accountability for IT management under FITARA.
Provide ongoing advice, risk reviews, and recommendations at Stage Gate Reviews. Review progress, mitigation plans, and make recommendations for improvement or continuation.

Establishes core activities and deliverables for IT projects, provides templates and tools, conducts audits of EPLC activities, and shares best practices for cost estimation, metrics, and project outcomes.
Ensure IT projects are technically sound and meet business needs. Conduct Stage Gate Reviews and decide whether to advance projects or require additional work. Operate according to approved charters.

Responsible for establishing governance processes that align with EPLC, ensuring critical partner participation, monitoring EPLC implementation, and working with leadership to maintain alignment with FITARA mandates.
Governs integrity of the EPLC Framework, receives and reviews change requests, accepts or rejects changes, requests additional information as needed, and provides feedback on policy changes.

Lists official HHS and federal guidance supporting this policy, including: EPLC Framework Overview, HHS Acquisition Regulation (HHSAR, 2015), Federal Acquisition Certification for Program/Project Managers (2013), Capital Planning and Investment Control (2016), IT Alternatives Analysis (2003), Earned Value Management (OMB M-05-23, 2005), IT Performance Management (2021), Enterprise Architecture (2008), System Inventory Management (2020), FITARA (OMB M-15-14, 2015), Cost Estimating and Assessment Guide (GAO, 2009), OMB Circulars A-11, A-127, and A-130, Records Management Policies (2020), Section 508 Accessibility Policy (2020), Security and Privacy Policies, and HHS Policy for Privacy Impact Assessments (2019).
The HHS OCIO Office of Enterprise Services (OES) manages this policy. Questions or requests for information should be directed to the EPLC resource mailbox: EPLC@HHS.gov.
The effective date of this policy is the date it is approved. OPDIVs must prepare implementation documentation within 120 days and provide a copy to the HHS CIO.

Implementation requires notification to labor unions and compliance with the Indian Self-Determination and Education Assistance Act and related policies. HHS must consult with tribal governments before taking actions affecting them and remove procedural impediments to such collaboration.
The effectiveness of this policy will be measured by: (1) percentage of IT projects using EPLC, and (2) percentage of IT projects using iterative/incremental development methodologies.
Refer to Appendix B of the EPLC Framework for definitions and terminology.
Acknowledges review and approval by the appropriate HHS officials. Future revisions must be coordinated and approved by the undersigned or their designated representatives.
